servings: 2
---

Halve, peel, and finely chop the @yellow onion{1}(finely chopped). Drain the @artichoke hearts{1%jar}, then coarsely chop. Finely chop the @parsley{1%bunch}(chopped), keeping the leaves and stems separate. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%clove}(minced).

Heat 1/2 tablespoon @olive oil{1.5%tablespoon} in a #medium pan{} over medium heat. Add half the onion and the parsley stems and season with @salt and @pepper. Cook for about ~{5%minutes}, stirring occasionally, until softened. Stir in the @basmati rice{3/4%cup} and cook for ~{2%minutes}, until lightly toasted. Add half the garlic and cook for another ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant.

Add 1 @veggie stock concentrate{1} and 1 1/2 cups water to the pan. Bring to a boil, reduce to a simmer, cover, and cook for ~{10%minutes}. Stir in the artichokes and @peas{4%ounce} and continue to cook, covered, for another ~{5%minutes}, until rice is tender. Set aside, covered, off the heat. No peeking!

Meanwhile, heat 1/2 tablespoon olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Season both sides of the @chicken breasts{2} with salt and pepper. Sear for ~{4-5%minutes} per side, until browned and juices run clear when pierced with a knife. Remove from the pan and set aside.

In the same pan you cooked the chicken in, heat another 1/2 tablespoon of olive oil over medium heat. Add the remaining onion to the pan and cook, stirring, for ~{5%minutes}, until fragrant. Add the second @veggie stock concentrate{1} and 1/4 cup water to the pan and simmer for ~{1-2%minutes}, until the sauce thickens slightly. Sprinkle in half the parsley leaves.

Thinly slice the chicken breasts against the grain. Fluff the rice pilaf with a #fork{}. Serve the chicken over the pilaf and spoon the sauce over top. Sprinkle with remaining parsley leaves and enjoy!

> Knowing how to make rice pilaf is a great trick to have up your sleeve - you can use the same technique with any variety of mix-ins or flavor profiles!